{
  "slug": "the-top-10-fantasy-films-the-toy-movie-hall-of-fame-and-mast",
  "title": "The Top 10 Fantasy Films, The Toy Movie Hall of Fame, and ‘Masters of the Universe,’ with Griffin Newman!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Griffin Newman"
  ],
  "published": "2026-06-05",
  "runtimeMin": 141,
  "format": "Sean and Griffin Newman start on a box office that keeps breaking their brains ('Obsession' still growing three weeks in), then dig into a metatextual 'Masters of the Universe' that has both their numbers and doesn't quite know what to do with them. Griffin builds a toy-movie hall of fame, they trade high-fantasy favorites, and Sean closes with an interview with Samara Weaving and director Adam Rehmeier about 'Carolina Caroline.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The state of the box office",
      "note": "with Griffin Newman",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Obsession",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Curry Barker's $750K indie horror, still growing in its third week: $5M on a Wednesday. Griffin can't find a comp inside his lifetime, opened wide and word-of-mouth built rather than crested. A down-the-middle scary movie, and the ordinariness is what makes the run so strange."
        },
        {
          "title": "Backrooms",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Kane Parsons' YouTube-born feature. Overperformed but is getting the classic 'what was all the noise about' backlash, unlike 'Obsession,' which seems immune to it."
        },
        {
          "title": "Weapons",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The comp Sean keeps reaching for: discourse around it, but people mostly landed on 'that movie is good.'"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Masters of the Universe’",
      "note": "the He-Man movie, 25 years in development",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Masters of the Universe",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Travis Knight directs; Nicholas Galitzine as Adam/He-Man, Camila Mendes as Teela, Idris Elba as Man-at-Arms, Jared Leto as Skeletor. Both had fun and both think it's wildly flawed, too long, and lands maybe a third of its jokes. The metatextual hook (Adam raised on Earth, a fan of his own lost world, a Barbie-in-reverse) is the smart part; the sincere-vs-satire tonal jumping is where it stalls. Leto, unrecognizable behind CGI, is the best thing in it. First live-action attempt since the 1987 Dolph Lundgren film."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The best high-fantasy movies",
      "note": "Sean went deep on the '80s canon and mostly came back to the obvious ones",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring",
          "year": 2001,
          "note": "Sean's high-water mark: builds a world, hands you characters you love instantly, makes you want the next stage of the journey without feeling tricked into it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The NeverEnding Story",
          "year": 1984,
          "note": "Saw it at roughly the age he's about to show his daughter."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Green Knight",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "The only recent pick: Lowery blending Arthurian and folkloric legend in an A24 silo."
        },
        {
          "title": "Princess Mononoke",
          "year": 1997,
          "note": "Watched with his daughter; still holds up, ecology and all."
        },
        {
          "title": "Willow",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "'Changed my life.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Dark Crystal",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "Griffin's addition to the canon: Henson pivoting into a darker realm."
        },
        {
          "title": "Excalibur",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "Griffin's other worthy-of-the-canon pick."
        },
        {
          "title": "Conan the Barbarian",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "The film that kicked off the '80s high-fantasy wave; Griffin calls it the source text."
        },
        {
          "title": "Labyrinth",
          "year": 1986,
          "note": "The other Henson film both consider special."
        },
        {
          "title": "The 7th Voyage of Sinbad",
          "year": 1958,
          "note": "Where they land on the Harryhausen question: one Ray Harryhausen film belongs, at least representationally."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Toy Movie Hall of Fame",
      "note": "Griffin's canon, and the catch is the good ones barely come from a product",
      "honoree": "Toy movies",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Barbie",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "With 'The Lego Movie,' the modern high-water mark: came from the cynical place and ended up somewhere fairly pure, honest about what adapting a piece of plastic means."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lego Movie",
          "year": 2014,
          "note": "The other one that succeeded creatively and wasn't ashamed of its source."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Lego Batman Movie",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "Griffin's particular love, though it drifts toward superhero and movie culture."
        },
        {
          "title": "Toy Story",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "Original characters, but the definitive take on kids and toys, and Griffin's favorite franchise."
        },
        {
          "title": "Transformers",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "The most satisfying key-jangling either of them gets in a theater; Griffin was at the premiere and it rocked his world."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Hudsucker Proxy",
          "year": 1994,
          "note": "Griffin's cheat pick: a whole movie about the hula hoop and the predatory business of toys."
        },
        {
          "title": "Raggedy Ann & Andy: A Musical Adventure",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Richard Williams' assignment-job nightmare, an existential toy movie before Toy Story. The camel's 'Blue' number is some of the best character animation ever."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Many Adventures of Winnie the Pooh",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "Griffin argues it in: A.A. Milne's boy-and-his-bear toys, the framing device a camera pushing into a child's room full of dolls."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dungeons & Dragons: Honor Among Thieves",
          "year": 2023,
          "note": "One of the rare genuinely good game-to-film results."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ouija: Origin of Evil",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "The second, Mike Flanagan Ouija movie: both agree it's really good."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "note": "on ‘Carolina Caroline’",
      "guest": "Samara Weaving & Adam Rehmeier on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Carolina Caroline",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A con-man crime romance Rehmeier directed but didn't write (Tom's script), which he steered from thriller toward a '70s-style romance. Shot chronologically over 25 days across ~100 locations; Weaving and Kyle Gallner's chemistry led them to rewrite the ending mid-shoot."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dinner in America",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Rehmeier's film that launched Kyle Gallner as an indie lead, cast off a single tintype that 'showed his soul.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Snack Shack",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "His curated 1991 summer movie; the reference point for how personal his needle drops usually are."
        },
        {
          "title": "Reds",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "Weaving's last great thing: saw it in the theater she and her partner built under the house. 'A masterpiece.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Jackass Number Two",
          "year": 2006,
          "note": "Rehmeier's pick: 'Jackass 1 and 2' at the New Beverly with Johnny Knoxville and Jeff Tremaine there, like being at a party."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
